      "text": "Potomac Economics releases 2024 ERCOT report | Potomac Economics posted on the topic | LinkedIn\n\nAgree & Join LinkedIn\n\nBy clicking Continue to join or sign in, you agree to LinkedIn’s User Agreement, Privacy Policy, and Cookie Policy.\n\n# Potomac Economics releases 2024 ERCOT report\n\nThis title was summarized by AI from the post below.\n\n2,915 followers\n\n10mo\n\nPotomac Economics has released our 2024 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT electricity market. As ERCOT’s Independent Market Monitor, we assess market outcomes, monitor for market power, and recommend design improvements to support efficient, reliable operations across the Texas grid. Key findings from this year’s report include: • A 52% decline in average real-time energy prices, primarily driven by a surge in new solar and storage capacity • Ancillary services costs fell by 74%—with energy storage resources supplying a growing share • Real-time congestion costs declined 17%, while congestion in the West Zone rose due to transmission constraints • No evidence of market power abuse, but structural risks indicate need for zonal and system-wide mitigation We continue to support ERCOT’s efforts to evolve market design in line with rapid changes in the region’s resource mix and load profile.#ERCOT#ElectricityMarkets#EnergyStorage#SolarPower#MarketMonitoring#PotomacEconomics#TexasGrid#ResourceAdequacy👇 View the full report from our website here: https://lnkd.in/e9xVZjPR\n\nElectric Reliability Council of Texas https://www.potomaceconomics.com\n\nNice, this will be fun to read while my analytics pipelines checks out tomorrow.\n\nReply 2 Reactions 3 Reactions\n\nLFG!\n\nReply 2 Reactions 3 Reactions\n\nWhen will the MISO 2024 State of the Market Report be available?\n\nTo view or add a comment, sign in\n\n650 followers\n\n6mo\n\nWe're delighted to have secured further funding from the Ofgem Energy Redress Scheme for our Energy Advice Service in collaboration with Citizens Advice Bury and Bolton. The Energy Advice Service provides home energy checks, help with switching tariffs and support to resolve issues with energy suppliers - ensuring the most vulnerable stay warm at home over the colder months 🏠💡\n\n932 followers\n\n6mo\n\nCongratulations to our recent Round 11 grantees for securing funding in phase two of the Ofgem Energy Redress Scheme. These projects have received funding through the Main Fund to support households who are most at risk from cold homes and high energy bills. Find out more about these projects and others: https://lnkd.in/ehFYnYky Age Concern Tyneside South Age UK Bolton KeyRing Living Support Networks Severn Wye\n\nTo view or add a comment, sign in\n\n6mo\n\nCalpine is receiving a $278.3 million to build a new natural gas power facility north of Houston. The loan is the fourth loan granted under the Texas Energy Fund. Two of the other TEF loans have been awarded to NRG Energy so far, with the other being awarded to Kerrville Public Utility Board. Read more about Calpine's new \"peaker plant\" at the Houston Business Journal.#power#electricity#loan#TexasEnergyFund https://lnkd.in/dbB_urYJ\n\nCalpine secures $278 million loan from Texas Energy Fund for new peaker plant - Houston Business Journal bizjournals.com\n\nTo view or add a comment, sign in\n\n30,383 followers\n\n6mo\n\nOntario company Northern Transformer Corporation recently announced their $206.8 million investment to establish a new manufacturing facility in Innisfil, Ontario. Creating 151 new jobs the project will double the company’s workforce and allow it to enter the Large Power Transformer market. The need for transformers is rising in North America due to increasing electricity consumption. By expanding domestic manufacturing of Large Power Transformers this investment will strengthen Ontario’s energy supply chain and its capacity to meet the growing demand for critical grid components. Learn more: https://lnkd.in/g55q7kcd#InvestInOntario\n\nTo view or add a comment, sign in\n\n1,614 followers\n\n6mo\n\nThe PJM region is sounding the alarm — and batteries are the answer. A new report from The Brattle Group for the U.S. Energy Storage Coalition shows the PJM grid faces an urgent reliability gap as demand surges and traditional generation slows to come online. 1. Peak demand is rising fast — up to +16 GW by 2028 and +30 GW by 2032. 2. The solution: at least 16 GW of 4-hour batteries needed by 2032, growing to 43 GW by 2045. 3. Without it: consumers face up to 30% higher costs and increased risk of load shedding. Why this matters now: 2025 is the final window to get batteries online before FEOC restrictions and tax credit limits tighten. Every project safe-harbored or procured today helps fill a gap the grid desperately needs filled by 2026. At GridVest, we’re helping developers and EPCs move fast — sourcing, financing, and warehousing compliant BESS to accelerate deployment and secure IRA benefits before deadlines close. The takeaway: The opportunity isn’t years away — contact GridVest to get a quote.#BatteryStorage#EnergyStorage#GridVest#CleanEnergy#SafeHarbor#PJM#EnergyTransition#FEOC\n\nTo view or add a comment, sign in\n\n4,692 followers\n\n6mo Edited\n\n🇺🇸 🚚 ⚡ We’re super thrilled to announce the appointment of Structured Capital LLC (SCLLC) as our private placement adviser for the San Luis Industrial Complex (SLIC) in Northern California. SLIC is an ambitious multi-phase large-scale industrial development precinct adjacent to the San Luis Reservoir in Northern California. Our first phase, the San Luis Transit Project, will harness local energy generation to produce advanced fuels for regional transportation fleets. Future phases will include data centres, advanced fuel facilities, and other energy-intensive industries drawn to the site’s proximity to the 500 kV Los Banos substation and large-scale energy resources. SCLLC will arrange strategic capital for the San Luis Transit Project and help accelerate subsequent phases, strengthening local economic development across California’s Central Valley. “SCLLC’s deep expertise in structuring capital for advanced fuel projects across the US makes them an ideal partner as we progress SLIC,” said Neal Aronson, Energy Estate’s US Director. This appointment reinforces Energy Estate’s commitment to developing industrial ecosystems that link California, Australia, and New Zealand. Read more: https://lnkd.in/dhFeUqi2 Neal Aronson Claire Speedy Simon Currie Vincent Dwyer Rosie King Everette Hull Mark Richards#California#SanLuisreservoir#SanLuisIndustrialComplex#SanLuisHydrogenTransitProject#StructuredCapitalLLC#datacentresUS#EnergyEstate\n\nTo view or add a comment, sign in\n\n6mo\n\nThe last coal-fired power plant in New England has closed, according to a Sept. 29 report in the Concord Monitor. The shutdown of the 438-megawatt, two-unit Merrimack plant in Bow, N.H., is three years earlier than the 2028 closure date announced just last year. The#coal plant is owned by private equity firm Atlas Holdings LLC through Granite Shore Power. According to the article, the plant ceased power generation on Sept. 12, and quotes Granite Shore President Jim Andrews as confirming that most of the staff has been laid off or transferred, and Merrimack is in now in the process of being permanently deactivated. Merrimack has run very little in recent years, surviving economically on capacity market payments from ISO New England Inc., the regional grid operator, which require the plant to provide power during critical demand times. Those payments, which were supposed to run through May 2026, appear to have been overshadowed by the plant’s high costs and maintenance challenges, including#pollution control problems in recent years. Last year, when the 2028 closure was announced, IEEFA North America reported that the end of capacity market payments in 2026 could lead to the plant shutting much earlier. (https://lnkd.in/enBnsJpu) This early closure, despite the 